ce:section.ce:para:
As an emerging type of QDs, carbon quantum dots (CQDs) not only exhibit similar advantages of other QDs mentioned above, but also have unique advantages including low cost, environmental friendliness, and flexible operability. Therefore, they can be applied in different interfaces or layers of PSCs[32,33]. Pang et al. modified SnO2 with graphene quantum dots, resulting in significantly increased open-circuit voltage (VOC
                     ) and short-circuit current (JSC
                     ), as well as optimized energy level structure [34]. Guo et al. utilized CQDs with abundant amino groups to passivate the perovskite film, leading to enhanced photoelectric performance and stability [35]. This highlights the role of QDs with functional groups in modification of perovskite layers. As a complex device system with several layers and interfaces, comprehensive performance of PSCs is determined by a series of factors. In another word, a single interface modification for addressing only one specific problem can hardly meet overall requirements of high-performance PSCs. Therefore, we believe that synergetic modifications of perovskite films with multi-functioned CQDs and investigation of their working mechanism are vital to development of PSCs.
